AWS:reInvent
------------

From SiliconANGLE ( https://siliconangle.com/2023/11/28/amazon-enhances-ser=
verless-data-platforms-kick-off-reinvent-2023/ ) :

Cloud computing giant Amazon Web Services Inc. kicked off its annual re:Inv=
ent 2023 conference this evening with a keynote address where it announced =
a trio of new capabilities that should make it easier for customers to use =
its serverless database offerings.

The headline announcement was the introduction of Amazon Aurora Limitless D=
atabase, which is a new feature for the Amazon Aurora database that can aut=
omatically scale beyond its original write limits, making it much easier fo=
r developers to scale their applications. Also announced were new capabilit=
ies for Amazon ElastiCache and the Amazon Redshift Serverless database, des=
igned to drive up workload performance while optimizing the platforms to ma=
nage costs.

I actually thought that this keynote from AWS SVP of Utility Computing Pete=
r DeSantis ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DpJG6nmR7XxI ) was really enj=
oyable: it wasn=E2=80=99t a typical enterprise keynote with logos and awkwa=
rd executive interviews, but rather a really good explainer of cloud comput=
ing generally and serverless specifically. To summarize briefly:

* It used to be that an enterprise had to buy a server, host it in a physic=
al space, provide networking, install software, and only then run their app=
lication.
* The initial wave of cloud computing took away the hardware parts of the e=
quation: now, instead of buying a server, you could rent one, complete with=
 hardware and networking. Then, you could install software like an operatin=
g system and the various frameworks you needed, and then run your applicati=
on.
* Serverless removes the need to maintain a server at all (thus the name); =
you don=E2=80=99t need to install an operating system and keep it up-to-dat=
e. You simply run your application using the appropriate APIs for the serve=
rless resources like compute and storage, and they are provisioned to your =
application on demand.

DeSantis started out by noting that serverless is the best possible manifes=
tation of the promise of cloud computing:

( https://videopress.com/embed/YyjJgLQy?hd=3D1&cover=3D1&loop=3D0&autoPlay=
=3D0&permalink=3D1&muted=3D0&controls=3D1&playsinline=3D0&useAverageColor=
=3D0&preloadContent=3Dmetadata )

These are the six most important attributes of a cloud computing service. T=
hese are the things that we spend a ton of time putting into all of our ser=
vices. But serverless services let us take these things a step further. For=
 example, serverless is more elastic, because we run over our vast infrastr=
ucture and share our capacity across a large number of customers, each cust=
omer workload represents a small fraction of the capacity. And serverless i=
s more cost-effective. Unlike a service where you have to pay for what you =
provision, with a serverless capability you only pay for what you use. And =
serverless computing allows us to run our infrastructure more efficiently, =
and that means better sustainability, because the most efficient power is t=
he power you don=E2=80=99t use. And because these services are built from t=
he ground up to run on AWS=E2=80=99s infrastructure, they deliver better se=
curity and better availability, taking advantage of native capabilities lik=
e AWS Nitro and our availability zone architecture.

The three announcements DeSantis made were about expanded serverless offeri=
ngs for relational databases, caching, and data warehouses (and to be fair,=
 not everything was truly serverless; the caching offering, for example, ha=
s a minimum usage size which means you=E2=80=99re paying a minimum fee rega=
rdless). There was a neat digression in the discussion about the database o=
ffering (Aurora Limitless) that described how AWS had to solve the problem =
of ensuring that servers anywhere in the world had the same time down to th=
e millisecond, so that timestamps could be used to keep events in sync; it =
was also interesting how the company is using machine learning to predict t=
he resources needed for data warehouse queries to provision capacity for mo=
re complicated requests.

