In every case the nature of Internet economics =E2=80=94 zero marginal cost=
s and zero transactional costs =E2=80=94=C2=A0make it viable for massive en=
tities that benefit from scale to service even the smallest of customers wi=
th the same capabilities that, in the analog world, were only available to =
intermediary entities like newspapers, networks, or retailers. Moreover, th=
ose capabilities are available at exceptionally low prices, particularly wh=
en you are just getting started: you can set up a blog, or upload a video t=
o YouTube, or set up a Shopify shop basically for free. This does, to be fa=
ir, increase the amount of bad writing or bad videos or cheap junk in the w=
orld, but it also provides the possibility for niche-focused and truly diff=
erentiated offerings to build viable businesses that reach the entire world=
.

So it is with software and serverless platforms like AWS. A single develope=
r can basically run a web application directly on AWS, with everything in t=
he middle, from hardware to operating system, completely abstracted away. A=
WS and other public clouds are providing the technical manifestation of a s=
miling curve.

That=E2=80=99s not to say that servers are going away: DeSantis himself not=
ed that there is a lot of legacy code that presumes the presence of an alwa=
ys-on server, and of course AWS will continue to support that. What he didn=
=E2=80=99t say, for understandable reasons, is there are also applications =
for which it makes much more economic sense to run an always-on server (lik=
e Prime Video ( https://www.primevideotech.com/video-streaming/scaling-up-t=
he-prime-video-audio-video-monitoring-service-and-reducing-costs-by-90 ) ):=
 a dedicated server on AWS is cheaper on a minute-by-minute basis than serv=
erless; the savings from the latter come from it running less of the time, =
having far simpler scalability capabilities, and not needing to have dedica=
ted developer operations teams. And, I would add, there are companies for w=
hich it makes sense to run their own dedicated datacenters, including hardw=
are, which is cheaper still on a minute-by-minute basis, albeit with even m=
ore complexity and even less flexibility.

None of that, though, changes the fact that it is serverless that is =E2=80=
=9Cnative=E2=80=9D to the inherent structure of the Internet. The Internet,=
 in industry after industry, favors the massive provider benefiting from sc=
ale, and the highly differentiated leveraging the cost structures that said=
 scale makes possible: everything in the middle is legacy.

AI Services
-----------

Again from SiliconANGLE ( https://siliconangle.com/2023/11/27/aws-enhances-=
ai-services-foundation-model-capabilities-improved-performance/ ) :

Amazon Web Services Inc. today announced a range of new artificial intellig=
ence service capabilities that are enhanced using foundation models. Announ=
ced at the annual re:Invent 2023 conference, the enhanced capabilities incl=
ude Amazon Transcribe now offering FM-powered language support and AI-enhan=
ced call analytics, Amazon Personalize now using FM to generate more compil=
ing content, and Amazon Lex now using large language models to provide accu=
rate and conversation responses.

There were no major new AI announcements from AWS (although the conference =
is still going on), but it is worth noting that a lot of actual AI use case=
s will look like this. To put it in the same framework I used for servers:

* Some small number of companies will have their own foundation models; thi=
s is like owning your own data center.
* A larger number of companies will fine-tune foundation models for their o=
wn use cases, likely using a service like AWS Bedrock; this is like running=
 your own server on a cloud provider.
* A huge number of applications will benefit from AI by incorporating speci=
fic capabilities via APIs available from their cloud provider; this is anal=
ogous to serverless.

These announcements fall in that last bucket: now an application on AWS can=
 have foundation-model driven translation, recommendation, or even chat res=
ponses, without needing to have their own foundation model or do extensive =
fine-tuning. Of course all of this depends on the underlying foundation mod=
els being good, but, as AWS wants to remind you, it also depends on the und=
erlying foundation models being reliable over the long run. To that end, th=
is comment from AWS CEO Adam Selipsky to SiliconANGLE about the OpenAI kerf=
uffle ( https://siliconangle.com/2023/11/27/reinvent-exclusive-aws-ceo-adam=
-selipsky-reveal-new-generative-ai-stack/ ) was exactly what you would expe=
ct:

We have been saying since we started laying out our generative AI strategy,=
 almost a year ago, how important it is for customers to have choice. Custo=
mers need multiple models =E2=80=93 there is no one model and no one model =
provider to rule them all. The events of the last few days have shown the v=
alidity and the usefulness behind the strategy that AWS has chosen. Custome=
rs need models they can depend on. Customers need model providers that are =
going to be dependable business partners. And customers need cloud provider=
s who offer choice and offer the technology that enables choice. Those clou=
d providers need to want to offer choice as opposed to being driven to prov=
ide choice. The importance of these attributes, which AWS has been talking =
about and acting on for more than 17 years, has become abundantly clear to =
customers in relation to generative AI.

It=E2=80=99s a fair argument!

